segments.text: Test 1, 2, 3.
Test 1, 2, 3.
This is the second hour of the interview with Mr. Benavides in regards to his time in Vietnam.
Mr. Benavides, in the beginning of the war, in the first few years the American public was in favor of the war, what do you think changed their views in regards to the war?

Well, I think that the generation, because of the freedom of speaking and the freedom that they have, or we have, is that they were exercising their freedom because they didn't approve of our involvement with that Asian country.
they saw a way where they, the young generation, the youngsters, would see a way where they could keep from going to fight an unpopular war.
I mean, who was the one that started, or who was against the United States?
No one.
It was that country, the South Vietnamese government, that needed assistance.

Probably the legislators saw a way to where they were supporting some of the large corporations, and they saw a need to where the economy would rise, where they would sell products where they would benefit, or the large corporations would benefit.
They started sending supplies and they sent us to guard those supplies.
We were, we didn't know who we were fighting with at the time, in the very beginning.
And so the radicals here in the United States, they didn't want to go because of that reason.
So what they did, they sort of demonstrated against our government.
This is some of the rights that all veterans fight for.
Well, there were five of them and eight of them, but they were doing it.
And some of them didn't go, and some of them went.
Some of them went two or three times.
Some of them died.
Now, those that went are telling their children, like I found mine, why we went.
It's helped us for a nation.
to keep the communism from spreading to our country, which they're close by.
Over here, they're south of Central America, the United States.
The people here just take too much for granted.
That's probably the reason why.
They had a way before they could keep from going, and so they didn't go.
Do you think that

you know, Westmoreland started, there were some statements made that General Westmoreland reports were coming back that we were winning the war, but yet we kept sending more troops and we were escalating.
Do you think that had any... No, I don't think, I don't think that General Westmoreland, General Westmoreland, I don't know, you know, I drove for him.
I think that
that there was a staff that he had that wasn't giving him the information that he wanted.
And so he was reported.
The general was never that much out in the field as he was, and every chance he got, he was out there.
But the legislators, that's why no one justified the divorce.
They kept him
So you feel like Westmoreland then was not informed as well by his staff?
Yes.
I think from what I guess I can gather is that his staff was just not...
In a way, his staff was probably thinking that they were going to help the general become more famous.
And...
Whether they knew it or not, I mean, anyone could say, hey, we killed 15 enemy over there.
Well, when the enemy was probably villagers.
And maybe out of those 15, seven were enemies.
The other were poor, innocent people.
Nevertheless, they were killed.
Do you think the bombing in the north increased the...
increase the North Vietnam's will to want to win that much more the more we bombed?
The more they, it gave them a, we won as far as the bombing, but it gave them a psychological lift, maybe?
Well, I think that the bombing increased because of our POWs and MIAs.
Yes, the Ho Chi Minh Trail was full of these people, the North Vietnamese that were coming through to fight us and to fight the South Vietnamese.
But psychologically, those bombs, let me tell you, that was like riders in the sky.
And anyone, I don't care,
how inhuman you are, but I mean, that's got a psychological factor involved in being paranoid.
So I don't think that that really stopped those, you know, those enemies that much.
I think that it was just us that didn't see
the way to hurt them or to become more effective than the Cold War.
We had, we could have won that war in two years, three years if, if, if poor General McMornell was left alone and, and commanded his troops the way a leader's supposed to command.
I'm not saying that he didn't command them, that, but a leader is more effective and, and, and chose more, uh, um,
of leadership to, in a place to where he, he is where he can most influence me.
And, and, and, and Hank, you pick up the paper and, you know, you, well now, we saw a team deal that I never did, that Frank Fortune never did, and that we were way, way back in the middle.
But, uh, you pick up the paper or anything and you listen to the radio and, and you say that, what, Manoa was ordered to Okinawa.
by some senator and congressman or what, that was more than was ordered to Hawaii.
And who was left running the ranch?
So, and then when they enfolded it, I'm one of them that's standing behind it 100%.
You know, LBJ was, he was pretty well, he was pretty well business oriented anyway.
He was out to help the, you feel like the,

a lot of, you know, he sent over a lot of people that were personal friends that owned big companies, and I know I did some readings where they, so many people came in to look at the war, and a lot of them were your scientists and your people with your big companies and stuff, and it said that that could have, you know, that Westmoreland had to spend time satisfying those people, you know.
Oh, well, you know, he, the general was one of them that
the commander of the commander-in-chief.
I mean, you just don't say no to the commander-in-chief, but you've got other people that are in second command that you trust can do the job just as well as you.
You know, you're the boss, but still, those are just those things that in our situation occur.
And I think that yes, those big corporations, they were, you know, they wanted to see one way
they could materialize, they could benefit by producing more machinery to the farmers there, by selling more fuel to the government.
the way we were flying, the way we were running our vehicles, to see in what way they could sell more trucks or jeeps or what.
And look what happened when they pulled out.
I'll get you one of those reports.
You can read it in Times Magazine in 1975, 72,
stated that there was $34 million worth of equipment left there for the enemy to have.
Do you feel like the South Vietnamese administration and Army really fought or tried to defend themselves as much as they could, or did they depend on the American Army too much?
I think they depended on the American Army too much.
Because, I mean, what's the sense of
of me sacrificing my life in my own country, trying to help with what I haven't got to help with, good weapons or what, or I'm not intelligent enough.
When I have you that are trained, and I have you to produce some equipment to help us in the war, I just sit back and I just lay down.

I know they, in some of the articles I've read, they said that the administration in Saigon was not really the best people that they would have wanted there to begin with, that he was a rich person looking out for himself.
He really didn't care about the peasants and villagers, you know.
You know, in some of those papers, I don't know which one it was,
There are some of those intelligence reports where there were some of these so-called rich Americans here that had money invested in those rubber plantations.
And I've heard it said, quote me or not quote me, but I've heard it said that there were some publications, some sort of an order said that
we would not fire into a rural plantation.
So you never heard of a jet firing into a rural plantation, even though the Indians went right in there.
What about the defoliation, the ranch hands?
Do you think that they should have done as much as they did, or was that another case of the big companies?
That's another case of the big companies.
Manzano was one of them that...
When I testified before the federal court in disagreeing that we, I still, I consider myself a victim of the agent law because I flew with the red flag.
And I was in an area where it was heavily sprayed.
I stated to the judge that
Why should we accept $180 million?
That's like saying that, hey, we're putting a price tag for the service of your country.
And we don't accept that because there's no price tag for us that serve our country.
There's nothing to say that, hey, we give you $200 million, $300 million, and that's it.
whether you live or die, but that's it.
We don't do it.
We show our country for the freedom that we're enjoying.
We listened to a speaker in our class that flew with the ranch hands, and he defended their
their view, he said that it was, all their spraying was necessary and that they did, that the trees would come back and all this.
And he defended, he was, he had the opposite view that you did.
Was he a doctor?
No, he was a pilot for the ranch family.
How did he know what that defoliation, what chemical that defoliation was?
He said that it was nothing more than stuff that we sprayed our crops here with.
Sure.
I believe him.
I believe anything he says.
Because when he went back
to his barracks, to his tent.
He took those clothes off that he had.
And he took a good shower.
He brushed his teeth.
We didn't.
We stayed two or three days with our own clothes.
We didn't take no bath.
Sure, I believe what he said.
But why wasn't he down on the ground with us?
And eating the food that we ate.
And sleeping under those trees.
I mean, did he go back again to see if those trees were
How many tours did he have in Vietnam?
I don't remember what he said.
I can understand, but yes, I believe him.
But I disagree with what he said.
Because he hadn't seen these youngsters here in Austin or over here in Houston or in Liberty or something.
In Dickerson, these youngsters, their fingers are just like toothpicks.
Their ears are...
or taped against their head.
He hadn't seen no jumpers.
And their father was right there.
And, no, he just flew, and then that's all.
He was an officer, and that's all.
But he wasn't on the ground.
I disagree with that.
I'm sorry.
You served, how many tours did you serve?
Two tours.
Two tours.
And your first tour was in?
It was there in the heavily, uh, uh, jungle area in Tamkeen, Kwanai.
I was an advisor to the Vietnamese Airborne Ranger Battalion there.
When we traveled, uh, we walked all through around the Black Virgin Mountains in those areas there.
And, uh, I used to, used to go to Pang Campound
there in Tam Kee and hitch a flight with them back to Da Nang or to Quang Ngai.
And we'd take Vietnamese villagers too.
We'd put little chickens in there and everybody carried their own little farm with them and little cages.
And I'd fly back to Tam Kee or Quang Ngai or wherever they were going to pick me up at.
And when was your second tour?
The second tour was in 68.
And that was after the war had really escalated, isn't it?
That was during the Tet Offense.
That was when our beloved President Johnson asked for, I think, 50,000 more troops.
And that was when the information was coming out that General McMorrin was asking for more troops.
He thought that we'd have the war won if we did more.
The Agent Orange spray did help us in a way, but there were some of those troops that were very disappointed and discouraged in what the government or the society back home were doing.
They were treated like third-class citizens.

They had no respect, no respect whatsoever for what we were doing, for what men quit school to go to serve their country, to protect the integrity of the President of the United States, to save this country from embarrassment.
And they burned the American flag.
They actually destroyed their own freedom
And right now, they're enjoying it.
They're enjoying it with one thought in mind.
When they hear about the soldiers, you know, they think in a way.
They think that right there at Rotary Club, the president of that Rotary Club right there was one of them that turned their back on them and went to Canada.
And he told them with tears in his eyes that I shamed him.
I said, no, I didn't shame you.
You shamed yourself.
I said, now you're back here in Houston, Texas, enjoying freedom that they've given my brother's life.
I said, you're a coward.
You could have been up there and saved two or three lives, even though it was a non-popular war.
Do you think that the United States people, every war we've been in before, the longest war we were ever in lasted only four years, and that was a civil war.
You think the American people just became so disillusioned because the war drug on so long, you know, that our mental state was that, you know, we go in and we win a war quick, and this one drug on.
Do you think that was part of the disillusionment?
I think that was one of the reasons of the government or society turning against us.
And I think that the other was the legislators.
Washington.
But why should we be blaming the American soldiers?
We're only obeying the orders of the American soldiers.
I mean, I'm proud to be a veteran of the Vietnam era.
Heck, even if I was a Korean veteran, which I served in Korea, too, right at the ceasefire time.
But I served my country, honestly, in a place where

And the public does not want to understand that soldiers are taken out, irregardless of whether that commander-in-chief, the president of the United States is wrong or right, he's got to obey those orders.
So why should he be condemned because he was ordered to go and fight in another country where it's an unpopular war?
Why not prosecute the legislators that
assisted the President, the Commander-in-Chief to send us over there.
Now, why did they approve those people, the lost son, and there was an accident and there was nine women that were lost and they were murdered.
Why are they so any guiltless now?
And how can they say that they're proud Americans?
They disobeyed the laws of the present.
And if those legislators can just tell us what they want done, and not tell us how they want us to do these things, that war could be won, I understand, in two years, three years.
Incidentally, the Civil War lasted four years, that's right.
The Second World War lasted four years.
But the hardest fighting of those four years
for almost six months, total of four years.
We fought for 10 years, 10 years, day and night.

We had to protect ourselves from our own shadow because we didn't know what little kid would come up and throw a hanger at us because he was doing it for food for his mother and father that this agent, enemy agent, would tell him,
Just throw that right there and I'll give you a case of food or I'll give you this.
Now, that little kid, he was an enemy to me.
If he threw a hanging egg, whether he realized it or not, I wasn't going to stand there and say, hey, little boy, you did wrong.
I mean, why?
That's why they call us baby killers and all that.
And what we didn't do regular or any...
any American would do in a case like that.
Get the hand grenade and throw it back at them again.
No, it was hard.
It was very hard for us.
And then to come back, and they spit on you in a uniform.
You, the defender of this country.
Those people who sit here and watch TV, a big ball game, while those guys are right now standing guard.
24 hours a day around this land of ours.
And what do we do?
We criticize our own, us, ourselves.
What do we do to these youngsters?
These youngsters won't want to go into the service.
They don't care.
But what about us after we're dead?
We won't worry about them.
If we ever have another war, do you think they'll have to use the draft?
I hope so.
I've always said, even in these schools where I talk,
You know, it's a matter of pride that, to be an American, you know, there's a saying, and I saw this, I saw a sign.
Did you read that buddy of mine that wrote just after, because of a certain neighbor right here who criticized me?
Yeah.
He said, for those that have fought for it, lives have a special flavor.
The protected ones never know.
And I think that every young man and woman, I'm not saying that they should, I think, that if they, they should donate two or three years of their time to the defense of this country.
Why wait until you graduate?
Sure you can go to college, but why not, you know, why not say, hey, I want to be part of a team?
You know, it's great when you
And you feel that Americanism in you.
When you hear that national anthem, you feel the cold shield up and down your arms.
And your heart kind of takes a deep beat.
Because that means you're proud.
You're proud to be an American.
And we only see those through color.
I think these youngsters, instead of getting high on drugs and booze, they get high on education.
do something for themselves, the community, and their country.
Because they're the future leaders.
You know, another thing that they blame, they say that a lot of the soldiers, you know, drugs, a lot of them got started on drugs over in Vietnam and brought that back here.
No, I tell you, there was more dope, cattle, and there was more marijuana smoke in one year in these colleges here than there was in 10 years in Vietnam.
See, you only hear the bad things.
You only hear the bad things.
You don't hear the good things.
Well, you heard that tape of the president.
They made a meet.
The news media, they're the worst.
They were, and now they're fighting against them, too.
Hey, why should they print this?
I mean, even, well, it's true or what?
Does the public really want to hear that?
Public, or do they want to see this?
They don't want to see that.
They only want to see what a good soldier does.
They know that we do bad sometimes.

So, you know, you feel, so a lot of times, a lot of the bad publicity that the war got was partially due to the news media because they only, what they showed on the TV to the people were things like my may lie and all that, you know, and that's what got all the publicity, not the
Not the rewards, y'all were, you know, the help that you got.
The building churches, helping the orphanage, helping the leprosy.
All they showed on TV was how many people were killed and how many, even women and children, and they really played this all up.
Those reporters, and I know because Peter Jennings was with them, he's a good, honest, truthful man, and he was right there with us.
I know because we flew together out of Kwong Nai.
He was wounded, I think.
He got sprained on his leg, I think.
We were getting shot up in bed that day.
But these reporters, they wouldn't go.
They wouldn't go to a village where we went and they'd see that little kid throw a hanging or that old lady throw a hanging or a hanging drop out.
They wouldn't show that kind of thing.
They'd take off like a scared jackrabbit.
But they would see if the soldier shouldn't.
Because they knew that they were V.C.
soldiers in North Washington.
That's what the public over here would see.
They wouldn't show up hanging and know they're going to get covered first.
And in a way, our own men did us wrong.
Our own, just to make themselves look good.
And they were telling themselves.
How come they wouldn't go with the special forces?
They didn't take too much with them.
Do you think that the involvement of moving the war into Cambodia and Laos also caused disillusionment with the American people?
Because here we weren't able to win the war in Vietnam, and now we were moving into two countries that the people considered weren't involved.
in the war?
No, but I don't think that we were moving the warrants there.
I think that we were just given permission.
That's when the North started finding out that we could win, that we were given permission to chase enemies there.
And the villages there, of course, they didn't want no part of it, and especially the bombing.
I think that
That the whole mess was just part of the legislators in our government.
They just didn't want us to win.
Because of production of materials.
It's big money.
That's right.
That war is going to become very famous in five years from now.
And enough soldiers.
are getting together more, especially the women veterans.
You know, they have bumper stickers.
Women are veterans, too.
And you should have seen this over there in Washington, the Memorial of Education.
I mean, there was women nurses that some of these men found that they hadn't seen in 15, 20 years.
There's one of them that threw herself over this patient because they were shelling that
That area, it's just like a mass unit.
And he has a very emotional side, let me tell you.
You know, two guys, they started crying, and that girl, all she could say, I love you, I love you, shut up.
Yeah, it was very emotional.
You see that these youngsters, when they go see the names on that wall, they thought it was their father there.
And then they read some good things about the veterans.
It's going to become, they're turning, they're turning, these youngsters now.
Especially, I don't, I didn't like to hear or read about that young lady that wouldn't stand up because of the National Anthem that played up in Massachusetts.
Maybe her parents, that's the way the kids are brought up.
But yet she's enjoying freedom.
She's enjoying going to the piece of HUD and everything.
And I know that she'd rather be here than be in
in Russia, in Czechoslovakia somewhere, to be told when to turn off the light and when to put it on, when to go out on the street and when not to.
So, we really don't realize what freedom we have until, unless we would go somewhere else and see how people live and how they're treated.
That's exactly right.
That is exactly right.
I have a book right there that was written by a priest that escaped chapter Leviticus.
And his greatest crime, now he wasn't a priest, he was a great athlete.
His greatest crime that they would...
